Simple Polling / SSE / WebSockets / WebRTC
---

# 🧠 1. Simple Polling

**What it is:**
Client repeatedly asks the server: *“Any updates?”* at fixed intervals.

**How it works:**

* Client → HTTP request every X seconds
* Server → responds (even if nothing changed)

**Pros:**

* Very easy to implement
* Works everywhere

**Cons:**

* Wasteful (many useless requests)
* High latency (depends on polling interval)
* Doesn’t scale well

**Use cases:**

* Basic dashboards
* Low-frequency updates

---

# ⚡ 2. Server-Sent Events (SSE)

**What it is:**
Server pushes updates to client over a **single long-lived HTTP connection**.

**How it works:**

* Client opens connection
* Server streams updates continuously

**Direction:**
👉 One-way (Server → Client only)

**Pros:**

* Efficient vs polling
* Simple (HTTP-based)
* Auto-reconnect built-in

**Cons:**

* Only server → client
* Limited browser support vs WebSockets (but still widely supported)
* Not ideal for binary data

**Use cases:**

* Notifications
* Live feeds (stocks, logs)
* News updates

---

# 🔄 3. WebSockets

**What it is:**
Full-duplex communication channel over a single TCP connection.

**How it works:**

* Starts as HTTP → upgraded to WebSocket
* Both client & server can send messages anytime

**Direction:**
👉 Two-way (bi-directional)

**Pros:**

* Real-time, low latency
* Efficient (no repeated headers)
* Supports binary + text

**Cons:**

* More complex than SSE
* Needs connection management (retries, scaling)
* Harder with proxies/firewalls sometimes

**Use cases:**

* Chat apps
* Multiplayer games
* Live collaboration (Google Docs-like)

---

# 🎥 4. WebRTC

**What it is:**
Peer-to-peer real-time communication (audio, video, data).

**How it works:**

* Browser ↔ Browser (direct connection)
* Uses signaling (often via WebSocket) to establish connection
* Uses STUN/TURN for NAT traversal

**Direction:**
👉 Peer-to-peer (no server in data path)

**Pros:**

* Ultra low latency
* Direct communication (reduces server load)
* Built for media (video/audio)

**Cons:**

* Complex setup (ICE, STUN, TURN)
* Hard to debug
* Not ideal for simple data updates

**Use cases:**

* Video calls (Zoom, Meet)
* Voice chat
* Peer-to-peer file sharing

---

# ⚖️ Quick Comparison Table

| Feature    | Polling         | SSE             | WebSocket      | WebRTC       |
| ---------- | --------------- | --------------- | -------------- | ------------ |
| Direction  | Client → Server | Server → Client | Bi-directional | Peer-to-peer |
| Latency    | High            | Low             | Very Low       | Ultra Low    |
| Efficiency | Poor            | Good            | Excellent      | Excellent    |
| Complexity | Very Low        | Low             | Medium         | High         |
| Connection | Many requests   | Single HTTP     | Persistent TCP | Direct P2P   |
| Best For   | Simple apps     | Live feeds      | Real-time apps | Video/audio  |

---

# 🧩 When to Choose What (Interview Answer)

* 👉 **Polling** → “When simplicity matters more than efficiency”
* 👉 **SSE** → “When you need real-time updates but only server → client”
* 👉 **WebSockets** → “When you need full-duplex real-time communication”
* 👉 **WebRTC** → “When you need peer-to-peer media or ultra-low latency”


# 💡 Golden Rule (Easy to Remember)

* **Start simple → Polling**
* **Optimize → SSE**
* **Real-time interaction → WebSockets**
* **Media / P2P → WebRTC**



